    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why AI Workloads Need Different Autoscaling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Standard HTTP request autoscaling \u2014 scale replicas up when CPU exceeds 70% \u2014 does not work for Claude API integrations. The bottleneck is not CPU in your application layer; it is Anthropic's rate limit. Your workers can be idle at 5% CPU while the request queue grows because all outbound slots are exhausted at the rate limit. Scaling up more workers in response to CPU would add workers that all hit the same rate limit wall."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Autoscaling for AI workloads requires a different signal: queue depth per worker, not CPU. The architecture decouples inbound traffic from outbound API calls using a request queue, scales workers based on queue depth, and enforces a rate limit guard in front of the API to prevent scale-out from exceeding the account quota. The queue absorbs spikes; the rate guard enforces the ceiling; the HPA controls the dequeue rate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Autoscaling architecture for Claude AI workloads: request queue + HPA workers + rate guard + Claude API with backpressure feedback loop",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Queue-Based Scaling Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The queue-based architecture has three components: an inbound request queue, a horizontally-scaled worker pool, and a rate limit guard. Each has a distinct responsibility."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inbound Request Queue"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "All Claude API requests are enqueued rather than dispatched directly to workers. The queue provides the key property that allows autoscaling to work correctly: it decouples the arrival rate (user traffic, potentially bursty) from the processing rate (rate-limited API calls). Requests that cannot be processed immediately wait in the queue rather than returning 429 errors to users."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Queue technology: Celery with Redis, AWS SQS, or Google Pub/Sub are all appropriate. The choice is driven by your existing infrastructure, not AI-specific requirements."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Queue depth visibility: the queue depth (number of pending messages) must be exported as a Prometheus metric or CloudWatch metric for HPA to consume."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Message TTL: set a maximum message age (e.g. 5 minutes for interactive requests, 24 hours for batch jobs) to avoid processing stale requests after the user has timed out."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Worker Pool (HPA-managed)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Workers dequeue requests and call the Claude API. The Horizontal Pod Autoscaler scales the number of worker replicas based on the queue depth per worker. The target is a configured queue depth per worker \u2014 when the average queue depth per replica exceeds the target, the HPA adds replicas."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# hpa-claude-workers.yaml \u2014 HPA for Claude API worker pool\napiVersion: autoscaling/v2\nkind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler\nmetadata:\n  name: claude-worker-hpa\n  namespace: production\nspec:\n  scaleTargetRef:\n    apiVersion: apps/v1\n    kind: Deployment\n    name: claude-worker\n\n  minReplicas: 2     # always keep 2 warm; cold start on 0->1 is 20-30s\n  maxReplicas: 20    # hard cap; rate guard enforces API limit below this\n\n  metrics:\n    - type: External\n      external:\n        metric:\n          name: celery_queue_depth\n          selector:\n            matchLabels:\n              queue: claude-requests\n        target:\n          type: AverageValue\n          averageValue: \"5\"   # target: \u22645 messages per worker replica\n\n  behavior:\n    scaleUp:\n      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 30    # scale up fast (30s window)\n      policies:\n        - type: Pods\n          value: 4                       # add up to 4 replicas per scale event\n          periodSeconds: 60\n    scaleDown:\n      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 300   # scale down slowly (5 min cooldown)\n      policies:\n        - type: Pods\n          value: 2                       # remove at most 2 replicas per scale event\n          periodSeconds: 60\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The asymmetric stabilization window is intentional: scale up fast (30-second window) to absorb traffic spikes before the queue grows deep; scale down slowly (5-minute window) to avoid thrashing when traffic is variable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rate Limit Guard"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The rate guard sits between the worker pool and the Claude API. It enforces a token bucket rate limiter that caps outbound request rate at the account's rate limit. When the limit is reached, it applies backpressure to the workers \u2014 not by dropping requests, but by delaying dequeue. This prevents the worker pool from issuing requests that will return 429, and prevents the HPA from adding more workers in response to 429 errors."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# rate_guard.py \u2014 token bucket rate limiter with backpressure for Claude API workers\nimport asyncio\nimport time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\n@dataclass\nclass TokenBucket:\n    \"\"\"Token bucket rate limiter \u2014 allows bursting up to capacity.\"\"\"\n    rate: float           # tokens per second (e.g. 16.67 for 1000 RPM)\n    capacity: float       # burst capacity in tokens\n    tokens: float = field(init=False)\n    last_refill: float = field(init=False)\n\n    def __post_init__(self):\n        self.tokens = self.capacity\n        self.last_refill = time.monotonic()\n\n    def consume(self) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Consume one token. Returns seconds to wait if bucket is empty.\"\"\"\n        now = time.monotonic()\n        elapsed = now - self.last_refill\n        self.tokens = min(self.capacity, self.tokens + elapsed * self.rate)\n        self.last_refill = now\n\n        if self.tokens >= 1.0:\n            self.tokens -= 1.0\n            return 0.0  # no wait needed\n        return (1.0 - self.tokens) / self.rate  # seconds until next token\n\n# Global rate guard: 1000 RPM with burst up to 60 requests\n_rate_guard = TokenBucket(rate=1000/60, capacity=60)\n_lock = asyncio.Lock()\n\nasync def rate_limited_call(client, **kwargs):\n    \"\"\"Call Claude API, respecting the token bucket rate limit.\"\"\"\n    async with _lock:\n        wait = _rate_guard.consume()\n    if wait > 0:\n        await asyncio.sleep(wait)\n    return await client.messages.create(**kwargs)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scaling Metrics and Targets"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Choosing the right scaling metric and target is critical. The target queue depth per worker determines the tradeoff between latency and cost: a lower target means more workers and lower queue wait time; a higher target means fewer workers and more queued time per request."
          }
        ]
      },
