      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For interactive Claude applications (chat interfaces, real-time suggestions), target 2\u20133 requests per worker. For asynchronous background jobs (document analysis, batch classification), 10\u201320 is appropriate. The target should never be 0 \u2014 that would cause runaway scaling because any queue message triggers replica adds."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Custom Metrics with KEDA"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Kubernetes HPA's External metrics support requires a metrics adapter. KEDA (Kubernetes Event-Driven Autoscaling) provides a simpler integration for queue-depth-based scaling across SQS, Redis, Celery, and other backends without a custom metrics adapter."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "yaml"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# keda-scaledobject.yaml \u2014 KEDA ScaledObject for Claude worker queue (AWS SQS)\napiVersion: keda.sh/v1alpha1\nkind: ScaledObject\nmetadata:\n  name: claude-worker-scaler\n  namespace: production\nspec:\n  scaleTargetRef:\n    name: claude-worker\n  minReplicaCount: 2\n  maxReplicaCount: 20\n  cooldownPeriod: 300     # 5-minute scale-down cooldown (matches HPA stabilization)\n  pollingInterval: 15     # check queue depth every 15 seconds\n\n  triggers:\n    - type: aws-sqs-queue\n      metadata:\n        queueURL: https://sqs.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/123456789012/claude-requests\n        queueLength: \"5\"          # target: 5 messages per replica\n        awsRegion: us-east-1\n        scaleOnInFlight: \"true\"   # include in-flight messages in depth calculation\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Handling 429 Rate Limit Responses"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the Anthropic API returns HTTP 429 (rate limit exceeded), the worker must not retry immediately. Immediate retry amplifies the problem: all workers retry simultaneously, generating a burst of requests that all also hit the limit. The correct pattern is exponential backoff with jitter and backpressure to the queue."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# retry_with_backoff.py \u2014 429-aware retry with exponential backoff + jitter\nimport anthropic\nimport asyncio\nimport random\nimport logging\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nasync def call_with_retry(\n    client: anthropic.AsyncAnthropic,\n    max_retries: int = 5,\n    base_delay: float = 1.0,\n    max_delay: float = 60.0,\n    **kwargs,\n) -> anthropic.types.Message:\n    \"\"\"Call Claude API with exponential backoff on 429 responses.\"\"\"\n    for attempt in range(max_retries + 1):\n        try:\n            return await client.messages.create(**kwargs)\n        except anthropic.RateLimitError as e:\n            if attempt == max_retries:\n                raise\n            # Exponential backoff with full jitter\n            delay = min(base_delay * (2 ** attempt), max_delay)\n            jitter = random.uniform(0, delay)\n            logger.warning(\n                \"Claude API rate limited (attempt %d/%d); retrying in %.1fs\",\n                attempt + 1, max_retries, jitter,\n            )\n            await asyncio.sleep(jitter)\n        except anthropic.APIStatusError as e:\n            if e.status_code in (500, 502, 503, 529) and attempt < max_retries:\n                delay = min(base_delay * (2 ** attempt), max_delay)\n                jitter = random.uniform(0, delay)\n                logger.warning(\"Claude API transient error %d; retrying in %.1fs\", e.status_code, jitter)\n                await asyncio.sleep(jitter)\n                continue\n            raise\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The `Retry-After` header in the 429 response contains the number of seconds to wait before retrying. When present, use that value as the base delay instead of the exponential calculation \u2014 it is more accurate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# read retry-after header for precise backoff\nexcept anthropic.RateLimitError as e:\n    retry_after = float(e.response.headers.get(\"retry-after\", base_delay * (2 ** attempt)))\n    jitter = random.uniform(0, retry_after * 0.2)  # \u00b120% jitter\n    await asyncio.sleep(retry_after + jitter)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scaling Limits and Safety Caps"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Autoscaling without a hard cap is dangerous. An infinite scale-out in response to a traffic spike can exhaust the rate limit and generate thousands of 429 responses simultaneously. The HPA maxReplicas setting must be calibrated to the rate limit: if your rate limit is 1000 RPM and each worker calls Claude at most 10 RPM (processing time ~6 seconds per request), you need at most 100 workers to saturate the limit. Setting maxReplicas above 100 for this scenario is wasteful and can cause runaway scaling."
          }
        ]
      },
