        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# max_replicas.py \u2014 calculate safe maxReplicas from rate limit and workload profile\ndef calculate_max_replicas(\n    rate_limit_rpm: float,\n    avg_request_duration_sec: float,\n    safety_margin: float = 0.80,  # stay at 80% of max to leave headroom\n) -> int:\n    \"\"\"\n    At steady state, each worker can process 60/avg_duration requests per minute.\n    To saturate rate_limit_rpm we need rate_limit_rpm / (60/avg_duration) workers.\n    Apply safety_margin to avoid saturating the rate limit completely.\n    \"\"\"\n    max_rps_per_worker = 60.0 / avg_request_duration_sec\n    workers_to_saturate = rate_limit_rpm / max_rps_per_worker\n    return int(workers_to_saturate * safety_margin)\n\nprint(calculate_max_replicas(1000, 6.0))   # \u2192 80\nprint(calculate_max_replicas(1000, 2.0))   # \u2192 25\nprint(calculate_max_replicas(5000, 6.0))   # \u2192 400\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scale-In Protection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Premature scale-in \u2014 reducing replicas before the traffic spike has fully subsided \u2014 causes the queue depth to spike again immediately after scale-in, triggering another scale-out cycle. This oscillation wastes time and resources. Three mechanisms prevent it:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Stabilization window: the HPA's scaleDown stabilizationWindowSeconds (300 seconds / 5 minutes is a safe default for AI workloads with variable response times)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Minimum replicas: keep at least 2 replicas at all times to avoid the cold-start cost when traffic resumes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Queue drain check: before the HPA can scale in, confirm the queue depth has been below the target for the full stabilization window \u2014 not just at the moment of the scale-in decision."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "A 5-minute scale-down cooldown costs roughly $0.05\u20130.20 in wasted replica runtime after a spike. Premature scale-in that causes a second scale-out costs 30\u201390 seconds of elevated queue latency for every user in the queue. The cooldown is almost always worth it."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Autoscaling AI workloads that call Claude requires queue-based architecture, not CPU-based HPA. Decouple inbound traffic from API calls via a request queue; scale workers based on queue depth per replica; enforce a token bucket rate guard in front of the Claude API to prevent scale-out from exceeding the account rate limit. Set maxReplicas based on the rate limit and average request duration \u2014 not arbitrarily high. Use asymmetric stabilization: scale up fast (30s), scale down slowly (5 minutes)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Scale signal: queue depth per worker (target 2\u20135 for interactive, 10\u201320 for batch), not CPU."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Rate guard: token bucket at the account's RPM limit; apply exponential backoff + jitter on 429."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use Retry-After header from 429 responses as the authoritative backoff duration."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "maxReplicas = (rate_limit_rpm / max_rps_per_worker) \u00d7 0.8 \u2014 calibrate to your rate limit."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Scale-down stabilization: 5 minutes; minimum replicas: 2 (avoid cold-start latency on traffic resumption)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
